00181 int
00182 HASH_INIT (SHA_CTX * c)
00183 {
00184 #ifndef OCTEON_OPENSSL
00185   c->h0 = INIT_DATA_h0;
00186   c->h1 = INIT_DATA_h1;
00187   c->h2 = INIT_DATA_h2;
00188   c->h3 = INIT_DATA_h3;
00189   c->h4 = INIT_DATA_h4;
00190   c->Nl = 0;
00191   c->Nh = 0;
00192 #else
00193   c->E = 0x67452301EFCDAB89ull;
00194   c->F = 0x98BADCFE10325476ull;
00195   c->G = 0xC3D2E1F000000000ull;
00196 #endif
00197   c->num = 0;
00198   return 1;
00199 }

00201 #define K_00_19   0x5a827999UL
00202 #define K_20_39 0x6ed9eba1UL
00203 #define K_40_59 0x8f1bbcdcUL
00204 #define K_60_79 0xca62c1d6UL

00206 /* As  pointed out by Wei Dai <weidai@eskimo.com>, F() below can be
00207  * simplified to the code in F_00_19.  Wei attributes these optimisations
00208  * to Peter Gutmann's SHS code, and he attributes it to Rich Schroeppel.
00209  * #define F(x,y,z) (((x) & (y))  |  ((~(x)) & (z)))
00210  * I've just become aware of another tweak to be made, again from Wei Dai,
00211  * in F_40_59, (x&a)|(y&a) -> (x|y)&a
00212  */
00213 #define   F_00_19(b,c,d)   ((((c) ^ (d)) & (b)) ^ (d))
00214 #define   F_20_39(b,c,d)   ((b) ^ (c) ^ (d))
00215 #define F_40_59(b,c,d)   (((b) & (c)) | (((b)|(c)) & (d)))
00216 #define   F_60_79(b,c,d)   F_20_39(b,c,d)
00217 
00218 #define BODY_00_15(i,a,b,c,d,e,f,xi) \
00219    (f)=xi+(e)+K_00_19+ROTATE((a),5)+F_00_19((b),(c),(d)); \
00220    (b)=ROTATE((b),30);
00221 
00222 #define BODY_16_19(i,a,b,c,d,e,f,xi,xa,xb,xc,xd) \
00223    Xupdate(f,xi,xa,xb,xc,xd); \
00224    (f)+=(e)+K_00_19+ROTATE((a),5)+F_00_19((b),(c),(d)); \
00225    (b)=ROTATE((b),30);
00226 
00227 #define BODY_20_31(i,a,b,c,d,e,f,xi,xa,xb,xc,xd) \
00228    Xupdate(f,xi,xa,xb,xc,xd); \
00229    (f)+=(e)+K_20_39+ROTATE((a),5)+F_20_39((b),(c),(d)); \
00230    (b)=ROTATE((b),30);
00231 
00232 #define BODY_32_39(i,a,b,c,d,e,f,xa,xb,xc,xd) \
00233    Xupdate(f,xa,xa,xb,xc,xd); \
00234    (f)+=(e)+K_20_39+ROTATE((a),5)+F_20_39((b),(c),(d)); \
00235    (b)=ROTATE((b),30);

00250 #ifndef MD32_XARRAY
00251   /*
00252    * Originally X was an array. As it's automatic it's natural
00253    * to expect RISC compiler to accomodate at least part of it in
00254    * the register bank, isn't it? Unfortunately not all compilers
00255    * "find" this expectation reasonable:-( On order to make such
00256    * compilers generate better code I replace X[] with a bunch of
00257    * X0, X1, etc. See the function body below...
00258    *                                    <appro@fy.chalmers.se>
00259    */
00260 # define X(i)   XX##i
00261 #else
00262   /*
00263    * However! Some compilers (most notably HP C) get overwhelmed by
00264    * that many local variables so that we have to have the way to
00265    * fall down to the original behavior.
00266    */
00267 # define X(i)   XX[i]
00268 #endif
